.TH RUFUSARM64-CLI 1 "15 July 2026" "RufusArm64 0.4.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
rufusarm64-cli \- safely create bootable USB media on Linux ARM64
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B rufusarm64-cli list
.RI [ --all ]
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B sudo rufusarm64-cli write
.BI --image " FILE"
.BI --device " /dev/DEVICE"
.RI [ options ]
.PP
.B sudo rufusarm64-cli verify
.BI --image " FILE"
.BI --device " /dev/DEVICE"
.PP
.B rufusarm64-cli hash
.I FILE
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B rufusarm64-cli
writes recognized GPT/MBR disk images and ISOHybrid Linux images directly, or
creates a modern GPT/FAT32 Windows UEFI installer from a standard Windows ISO.
Large Windows installation images are split before the target is erased.
.SH WRITE OPTIONS
.TP
.B --verify
Flush block buffers and verify data after writing. Recommended.
.TP
.B --yes
Skip the interactive destructive-operation confirmation.
.TP
.B --allow-fixed
Permit a non-removable whole disk after all other safety checks pass.
.TP
.B --force-raw
Expert override that forces raw writing of a deliberately unrecognized or plain optical image.
.TP
.B --no-unmount
Do not issue initial unmount commands. The operation is still refused if a
filesystem is mounted at the final safety check.
.TP
.B --dry-run
Perform basic discovery, signature, size, and target-safety checks without writing. Windows ISO mounting and payload validation occur only during the privileged creation operation.
.TP
.B --expected-identity " TOKEN"
Require the selected device to match a token returned by the JSON list command.
The graphical application always supplies this fail-closed check.
.SH SAFETY
The program refuses partitions, read-only targets, the running root disk, and an
image stored on the selected target. It refreshes device identity immediately
before destructive work, locks the target, removes stale signatures, flushes
kernel block buffers, and verifies before requesting a partition-table reread.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Zero indicates success. A non-zero status indicates refusal, cancellation,
validation failure, I/O failure, filesystem failure, or verification mismatch.
